g business, the workplace, or government. But this is the first book about something much more fundamental: how the internet is transforming our collective intelligence and our understanding of the world. From the collaborative mathematicians of the Polymath Project to the amateur astronomers of Galaxy Zoo, Reinventing Discovery tells the exciting story of the unprecedented new era in networked science. It will interest anyone who wants to learn about how the online world is revolutionizing scientific discovery—and why the revolution is just beginning.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aDiscoveries in science. 0aInformation networks. 0aInformation technology. 0aInternet. 0aResearchxTechnological innovations. 7aSCIENCE / Research & Methodology.2bisacsh  aAdvertising.  aArXiv.  aAstronomy.  aBiologist.  aBiology.  aBlog.  aBlogger (service).  aCalculation.  aCareer.  aChris Lintott.  aCitizen science.  aCognitive Surplus.  aCollaboration.  aCollective intelligence.  aComparative advantage.  aCompetition.  aComputer programming.  aComputer.  aConsideration.  aCreative work.  aDecision-making.  aDivision of labour.  aElinor Ostrom.  aEmail.  aFoldit.  aGalaxy Zoo.  aGalileo Galilei.  aGenBank.  aGroup work.  aGroupthink.  aIT Works.  aInformation commons.  aIngenuity.  aInnoCentive.  aInstance (computer science).  aInternet forum.  aJames Surowiecki.  aJon Udell.  aLee Smolin.  aLinus Torvalds.  aLinux kernel.  aLinux.  aMainstream media.  aMass collaboration.  aMathematical problem.  aMathematician.  aMathematics.  aMicrosoft.  aNetwork science.  aOnline and offline.  aOnline community.  aOnline discussion.  aOpen data.  aOpen science.  aOpen-source software.  aOpenness.  aPLOS.  aParticipant.  aPh